Worked for 1m 39s
Findings

[P0] The receipt contract as planned does not actually anchor the demo to ERC-8004 identities. Fragment stores only address contributor, and borrowFragment(fragmentId) has no borrower agent ID, so your on-chain receipt cannot cleanly join to portable identity/reputation later. For this concept, I’d treat contributorAgentId and borrowerAgentId as first-class receipt fields or emitted event fields, not an off-chain script detail.

[P0] borrow-fragment.ts currently pays before proving the fragment is retrievable and matches the hash. The plan says: pay ETH, then fetch content, then verify hash. If the URI is down or the content changed, the borrower has already paid and there is no recovery path. For an MVP, the script should fetch and hash-check first, then send the purchase tx.

[P1] The ERC-8004 contingency tree is stale and could send you into unnecessary cross-chain complexity. Current ERC-8004 materials indicate testnet deployments already existed by October 15, 2025, and the spec is designed for per-chain deployments, so “if not on Sepolia, register on mainnet” is a bad fallback because it splits identity/reputation from the Sepolia demo flow. Pick one chain story and keep identity, receipts, and feedback on that same chain. Sources: EIP-8004, 8004.org.

[P1] The evaluation harness is under-specified relative to how central it is. “Run Claude, then Claude judges both outputs” is very demo-fragile: you can get noisy or self-serving scores, and on a bad task there may be no measurable delta. Lock a tiny benchmark set now, blind the order, require structured scoring JSON, and produce a human-readable evidence diff alongside the score.

[P1] serve-fragments.ts is fine for local iteration, but if the on-chain contentURI ends up being localhost, the demo is not reproducible for judges or anyone watching later. For the submission path, use a public static URL or IPFS, even if local HTTP stays in the dev loop.

[P2] The scope still looks a little too wide for the actual calendar. Today is March 20, 2026 and your deadline is March 22, 2026. With zero code in the repo, I would demote getFragmentsByDomain, demo.ts, and possibly even register-agent.ts from “cut if behind” to “only build if the core flow is already green.”

[P2] The verification bar for ERC-8004 is too low. “Confirm ERC-721 minted” is not enough; the spec’s value is the registration file and wallet metadata, not just minting a token. register-agent.ts should validate that the agentURI resolves to a valid registration document, otherwise you may claim standards integration without demonstrating the standards-shaped artifact. Source: EIP-8004.

Open Questions / Assumptions

If “compensation on Ethereum” is part of the pitch, Sepolia only gives you demo money. If that matters, the current plan should say “testnet proof of flow” explicitly.
Your own research note currently recommends a lighter split: identity/reputation via ERC-8004, receipts via a small custom contract, and off-chain memory content/public URLs. That still matches the concept and is less risky than expanding the lending contract’s responsibilities. See onchain-agent-infra.md and memory-fragment-formats.md.
Bottom Line

The plan is directionally strong, but I would change three things before building: put ERC-8004 agent IDs into the receipt flow, never pay before off-chain verification, and reduce scope immediately around the evaluation harness. If you do that, the scaffold stays compatible with the TBD fragment format and is much less likely to collapse under demo pressure.


